Basic Linux commands every DevOps Engineer must know:
File and Directory Management
pwd → Show current working directory
ls → List files and directories
ls -l → Long listing with permissions
ls -a → Show hidden files
cd <dir> → Change directory
mkdir <dir> → Create new directory
rmdir <dir> → Remove empty directory
rm -rf <dir> → Remove directory with all contents (:warning: careful!)
cp file1 file2 → Copy files
mv file1 file2 → Move or rename file

File Viewing & Editing
cat file → Show file contents
less file → View file page by page
head -n 10 file → Show first 10 lines
tail -n 10 file → Show last 10 lines
tail -f file → Monitor file in real time (useful for logs)
nano file / vim file → Edit file

File Permissions
ls -l → View permissions
chmod 755 file → Change permissions
chown user:group file → Change ownership
:small_blue_diamond: Process Management
ps aux → List processes
top → Monitor running processes
htop → Better interactive process viewer (if installed)
kill -9 <pid> → Kill process by ID
systemctl status service → Check service status
systemctl start/stop/restart service → Manage services

Disk & Memory
df -h → Show disk space usage
du -sh <dir> → Show directory size
free -h → Show memory usage
uptime → Show system load and uptime

Networking
ifconfig / ip addr → Show network interfaces
ping <host> → Test connectivity
curl <url> → Fetch data from URL
wget <url> → Download file
netstat -tulnp → Show listening ports (or ss -tulnp)
scp file user@host:/path → Securely copy file to remote server
ssh user@host → Connect to remote server

User Management
whoami → Show current user
id → Show user ID and groups
adduser <username> → Add new user
passwd <username> → Change password
su - <user> → Switch user
groups → Show user groups

Package Management (depends on distro)
Debian/Ubuntu:
apt update → Update package list
apt install <pkg> → Install package
apt remove <pkg> → Remove package
RHEL/CentOS:
yum install <pkg> → Install package
yum remove <pkg> → Remove package

Logs
cd /var/log → Go to log directory
tail -f /var/log/syslog → Live view logs (Debian/Ubuntu)
tail -f /var/log/messages → Live view logs (RHEL/CentOS)

Archiving & Compression
tar -cvf archive.tar files/ → Create tar archive
tar -xvf archive.tar → Extract tar archive
gzip file → Compress file
gunzip file.gz → Decompress file

Search & Find
find /path -name filename → Find files by name
grep "text" file → Search text in file
grep -r "text" /dir/ → Recursive search
history → Show command history
